parts.text:
USER PRIORITY INSTRUCTION (CRITICAL): {{30.refinement}}

HYPER-REALISM & AUTHENTICITY ENGINE (MANDATORY): Final Output Objective: A RAW, high-end commercial fashion photograph. Absolutely NO "AI-smoothing," NO plastic skin, and NO digital-render look.

The Model (Victoria/Alma): Maintain hyper-realistic skin integrity. Show natural imperfections, fine peach fuzz, and visible skin pores. Lighting must create natural subsurface scattering on the skin, especially around the neck and collarbone.

The Jewelry (The "Real-Deal" Law): The jewelry must NOT look like a digital overlay. It must exhibit "Optical Authenticity":

Refraction & Dispersion: Emeralds/Moissanites must show internal light refraction and "fire" consistent with professional jewelry photography.

Metal Physics: Gold/Silver must show realistic micro-scratches and reflections of the environment.

Zero-G Prohibited: The piece must show physical interaction with the body—slightly depressing the skin where it rests and casting a sharp, realistic micro-shadow.

Camera Specs: Shot on 35mm lens, f/2.8, natural film grain, authentic color science. If it looks "too perfect," it is a failure. It must look human and handmade


"Apply these specific parameters for this generation:

Image Format: Use aspect ratio {{30.aspect_ratio}}. 

Visual Consistency: Influence level is {{30.influence}}. High level means stick strictly to Victoria's known features.

Magic Refine (Critical): {{30.refinement}} (This is a one-time priority instruction from the user. Follow it precisely!)".


THE "ANTI-BULK" SCALE LAW (CRITICAL & ABSOLUTE): You are a luxury jewelry expert specializing in ultra-fine, dainty, and delicate pieces. Your biggest enemy is oversized, costume-looking jewelry.

The Single Truth: Look at image_input[1] (the model reference). The jewelry size on her body is the MAXIMUM allowed size. It is tiny and subtle.

The Shrinking Command: The object in the studio shot (image_input[0]) is taken with a macro lens. You MUST visually REDUCE its scale by 500% when placing it on Victoria (image_input[2]).

Negative Constraints (What NOT to do):

Do NOT make it "statement jewelry".

Do NOT let the chain look thick or heavy.

Do NOT enlarge the pendant to show detail. It must be a tiny sparkle on the skin.

Final Check: If the generated jewelry looks any thicker or larger than the reference in image_input[1], IT IS WRONG. Force it to be smaller, finer, and barely there.

THE EYE-IRIS SCALE RULE (MANDATORY): The pendant size on Victoria's neck MUST be smaller than the iris of her eye.
It must be a tiny, subtle sparkle. Mimic the exact micro-scale seen in image_input[1]. Do NOT enlarge the piece to show details. If it's larger than her eye's iris, it is a failure.

### THE "ULTRA-REALISM" INTEGRATION PROTOCOL (CRITICAL): You are a world-class fashion photographer. Your goal is to make the jewelry look physically present on the skin, NOT overlaid.

Gravity & Contours: The chain must not float. It must physically rest ON the skin, following the exact curves of Victoria's clavicle (collarbone) and neck muscles. It should show slight weight, pressing subtly into the skin texture.

Contact Shadows: This is the most important rule for realism. The jewelry MUST cast tiny, soft, realistic contact shadows onto the skin directly beneath it. Without these micro-shadows, it looks fake.

Environmental Reflection: The metal and gems must reflect the environment (e.g., the warm light of the yoga studio, the window light). The gold/silver should not look flat; it must interact with the light sources in the scene.

Skin Texture Interaction: The jewelry sits within the texture of the skin, not above it. The skin pores and fine lines should be visible right up to the edge of the metal.

Photographic Style: RAW, unfiltered photo. Natural film grain. Focus is sharp on the jewelry and the skin texture beneath it. No "AI smoothing" or plastic look.
